Likelihood and output data type¶

When we have COUNT output, the level of variation changes as the AVERAGE number of events changes!!!!

We cannot use "regular" regression with linear models because we need the VARIANCE of the OUTPUT to change as the input changes!!!!! Regular linear models assume the output variance is CONSTANT!!!!!!

The output data type dictates the LIKELIHOOD which dictates the kind of model we can use!!!

Continuous outputs - regression with Gaussian likelihood.

Binary outputs - classification with logistic regression via Bernoulli likelihood.

Count outputs - Poisson regression via Poisson likelihoods.

If we MISTAKENLY fit a linear model to predict the AVERAGE COUNT...we can have NEGATIVE NUMBERS!!! Do NOT do the following when working with COUNT DATA!!!!

In [27]:
sns.lmplot( data = lfB, x='value', y='y', col='variable' )

plt.show()

Fit models¶

We do NOT need to preprocess the INPUTS for this application because all inputs are centered around 0 already with roughly the same scale.

We will fit the models using Poisson regression via statsmodels. The interface is VERY similar to "regular" linear models via smf.ols() and logistic regression via smf.logit().

The basic function call is smf.poisson().

Let's start very simple with an INTERCEPT-ONLY or UNKNOWN constant average model!!!!

Poisson regression does NOT have an analytic or closed form expression for the regression coefficients, just like Logistic regression. There is NO OLS formula for Poisson regression!!! An optimization algorithm is used behind the scenes to estimate the coefficients.

In [28]:
mod_00 = smf.poisson( 'y ~ 1', data = dfB ).fit()

Optimization terminated successfully.
         Current function value: 3.513381
         Iterations 1

The intercept estimate is below.

In [29]:
mod_00.params
Out[29]:
Intercept    1.016934
dtype: float64

The intercept does NOT equal the average output!

In [31]:
dfB.y.mean()
Out[31]:
2.764705882352941

Behind the scenes, Poisson regression does NOT model the average output or average count directly!!!

Instead, we model the log average output!!! The intercept is therefore the log average counts!!!!

This is analogous to how logistic regression does NOT model the probability of the event. Instead, logistic regression models the log-odds ratio!!!!!!

The average output is therefore TRANSFORMED and we provide a LINEAR MODEL on the TRANSFORMED OUTPUT!!! The transformation function is known as the LINK FUNCTION.

We must apply the INVERSE LINK to calculate the average output from the estimated INTERCEPT!!! The inverse link for Poisson regression is the exponential.

In [32]:
np.exp( mod_00.params )
Out[32]:
Intercept    2.764706
dtype: float64

Basically...we cannot use smf.ols() even though the OUTPUT is a number!!!

Let's now fit some more meaningful models...just to demonstrate let's begin by using each input separately.

In [36]:
def my_coefplot(model_object, figsize_use=(10,5)):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize_use)
    
    ax.errorbar(y = model_object.params.index,
                x = model_object.params,
                fmt = 'o', color = 'black', ecolor='black',
                xerr = 2 * model_object.bse,
                elinewidth = 3, ms = 10)
    
    ax.axvline(x=0, linestyle='--', linewidth=5, color='grey')
    
    ax.set_xlabel('coefficient value')
    ax.set_ylabel('coefficient name')
    
    plt.show()

The Pseudo Rsquared requires taking the RATIO of the model's log-likelihood with an INTERCEPT-ONLY model's log-likelihood.

Out[41]:

This is identical to the Model's Pseudo Rsquared attribute .prsquared:

In [44]:

Out[44]:
0.386547074476158

This means, each smf.poisson() function call actually fits TWO models...the model you provide with the formula and the intercept only model!!!!

I prefer AIC/BIC to identify the best model when only considering the training set. We know that AIC/BIC automatically penalizes based on the number of features!

I rarely recommend fitting models one input at a time! The previous exercise was done just for teaching purposes. Instead, start with an intercept-only model, then fit a model with all categorical inputs with additive features, then fit a model with all continuous inputs with linear additive features, then fit a model with ALL inputs with linear additive features.

Since we do not have categorical inputs in this example, we will fit a model with ALL continuous inputs with linear additive features.

Check validity of Poisson regression¶

The fundamental assumption of the Poisson likelihood is that the VARIANCE equals the MEAN!!!!

BUT...we must be careful...this idea does not apply to the MARGINAL distribution of the output!!!

In [70]:
dfB.y.mean()
Out[70]:
2.764705882352941
In [71]:
dfB.y.var()
Out[71]:
23.58352941176471

But the Variance equaling the mean assumption corresponds to the REGRESSION MODEL!!!!!!!!!!! Or, the variability around the TREND increases as the TREND increases. The Variance around the trend is equal to the TREND itself! Thus, the Variance around the trend DEPENDS on the inputs!!!!!!

We therefore need to confirm that the Poisson assumption of Variance = Mean is in fact valid!

A simple check is based on the idea that the VARIANCE equals something other than the MEAN:

$$\mathrm{Variance} = \mathrm{Mean} + \alpha \times \mathrm{Mean}^2$$

If the AUXILLARY SLOPE, $\alpha$, is ZERO, then the VARIANCE equals the MEAN and the Poisson regression is valid.

We need the model "fits" of the average count in order to calculate the AUXILLARY test statistic.

Let's do this for the best model according to AIC.

In [73]:
mod_05.fittedvalues[:5]
Out[73]:
0    0.594802
1   -1.439898
2   -1.987421
3   -1.078913
4   -1.943123
dtype: float64

We will compare the observed COUNT to the FITTED COUNTS...thus we much undo the LINK or calculate the INVERSE LINK of the .fittedvalues attribute.

In [74]:

Out[74]:
0    1.812672
1    0.236952
2    0.137048
3    0.339965
4    0.143256
dtype: float64

Let's create a copy of the training set to separate the validity calculations from the rest of the problem.

In [78]:

Include the fitted average counts in the new data set.

In [79]:

Calculate the new auxillary statistic.

In [81]:
df02['t'] = ( (df02.y - df02.avg_count)**2 - df02.avg_count ) / df02.avg_count

The auxillary linear model does NOT include an intercept. We are thus only estimating the slope.

In [82]:
aux_mod = smf.ols( 't ~ avg_count - 1', data = df02).fit()
In [83]:
my_coefplot( aux_mod )

If the auxillary model's slope was statistically significantly POSITIVE...then the Poisson regression assumption of Variance = MEAN is NOT valid!!!!!!

If Poisson regression is NOT valid, then we need more flexible LIKELIHOODS. The negative binomial likelihood is a popular overdispersed likelihood for count data.

However, we are NOT confident in the SIGN of the auxillary slope! Thus, the Poisson regression assumptions are VALID for the data and model!

In [ ]:
